      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nI came to a conclusion that I really don't understand this test and don't see how it becomes fixed with this change.\n\nFirst, we test file size before comparison, so how there could be EOF?\n\nSecond, how can you so boldly calculate remainder amount, it's not that you lock the file, as such why cannot dd keep moving forward and you by the time you query the file size, there is some progress and a mixup of data as the result.\n\nthen you reduce dd size - does this hide the problem so that dd terminates faster and the remainder is always zero? Then the test is mostly useless?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "66eb675168eef87944e8ead52d7c322cbadda1b9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-03-01 14:00:37.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n\"First, we test file size before comparison, so how there could be EOF?\"\n\nBecause we're comparing the file content between file1 and ref2. From the failure, the size of ref1 is 47M, and ref2 is 30M. Dd copied 42M when swapping happened so copied=42M. After files are swapped, size of file2 will be 42M, and file1 will be 47M. Also the file content of file1 is: {30M ref2, sparse, 5M from ref1}.\n\nAfter file are swapped, the size of file2 is fixed which is exactly how many bytes it copied. Reducing dd block size definitely makes copying slower so I'm not sure I understand your comment.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
